{
  "interpretation": "Intensive-margin Frisch elasticity: percent change in annual hours worked among prime-age US workers who remain employed, in response to a 1 percent change in the net-of-tax wage holding the marginal utility of wealth constant, as used in lifecycle or macro calibration.",
  "point_estimate": 0.5,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.1,
    "p25": 0.3,
    "p50": 0.5,
    "p75": 0.8,
    "p95": 1.5
  },
  "citations": ["Pistaferri (2003), Journal of Labor Economics, PSID-based estimates of the Frisch elasticity", "Chetty (2012), Econometrica, bounds on elasticities with optimization frictions", "Keane (2011), Journal of Economic Literature, survey of labor supply elasticities"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Micro IV estimates for prime-age men with instrumented wage changes are often quite small (roughly 0.1-0.35, e.g., Altonji-style estimates), while estimates correcting for measurement error and using subjective wage expectations (Pistaferri) center nearer 0.7; women's intensive-margin responses are typically larger. Surveys of the literature (Keane) place central intensive-margin Frisch values around 0.3-0.5, and calibration practice often adopts ~0.5-1.0, though those figures frequently embed participation responses that this definition excludes. Combining these, I center at 0.5 with wide dispersion: the literature spans near-zero to values above 1 depending on instrument, sample, and treatment of measurement error, so p05 near 0.1 and p95 near 1.5 reflect genuine parameter and specification uncertainty."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Intensive-margin Frisch elasticity: percent change in annual hours by already-employed prime-age US workers in response to a 1% change in the net-of-tax wage, holding the marginal utility of wealth constant (no participation/extensive margin), as used in lifecycle or macro calibration.",
  "point_estimate": 0.5,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.1,
    "p25": 0.3,
    "p50": 0.5,
    "p75": 0.8,
    "p95": 1.5
  },
  "citations": ["MaCurdy (1981) intertemporal labor supply estimates", "Chetty, Guren, Manoli & Weber (2011) on micro vs macro intensive-margin Frisch elasticities", "Pistaferri (2003) using subjective expected wage changes"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Micro estimates of the intensive-margin Frisch elasticity for prime-age workers (mostly men) cluster around 0.3-0.7 once optimization frictions are considered, with some smaller values near 0.1-0.2 in early IV work. Macro and lifecycle calibrations often assume 0.5-1.0, and occasionally higher. I center my distribution at 0.5, with the bulk of mass between 0.3 and 0.8, a lower tail to ~0.1 reflecting small micro estimates, and an upper tail to ~1.5 reflecting high-calibration values."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Intensive-margin uncompensated (Marshallian) elasticity of annual hours worked with respect to the net-of-tax wage, for prime-age US workers already employed, excluding participation adjustments.",
  "point_estimate": 0.15,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.05,
    "p25": 0.05,
    "p50": 0.15,
    "p75": 0.30,
    "p95": 0.50
  },
  "citations": ["MaCurdy (1981), An Empirical Model of Labor Supply in a Life-Cycle Setting, JPE", "Blundell & MaCurdy (1999), Labor Supply: A Review of Alternative Approaches, Handbook of Labor Economics", "Chetty, Guren, Manoli & Weber (2011), Are Micro and Macro Labor Supply Elasticities Consistent?"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Micro studies of prime-age men (MaCurdy; Altonji) find intensive uncompensated hours elasticities near zero or slightly negative as substitution and income effects roughly offset. Estimates for women and broader samples are higher, often 0.2-0.5. Since the population is all prime-age workers already working, I center the median modestly positive around 0.15, with a left tail allowing a small negative value (income effect dominating for some groups) and an upper tail reaching about 0.5 to accommodate higher female and friction-adjusted estimates."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Medium-run employment/labor-force participation elasticity of U.S. single mothers with respect to the net-of-tax wage: percent change in participation for a 1 percent change in the net-of-tax wage.",
  "point_estimate": 0.6,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.2,
    "p25": 0.4,
    "p50": 0.6,
    "p75": 0.9,
    "p95": 1.3
  },
  "citations": ["Eissa & Liebman (1996), Quarterly Journal of Economics, EITC and single mothers' labor supply", "Meyer & Rosenbaum (2001), Quarterly Journal of Economics, welfare reform/EITC and single mothers' employment", "Keane & Moffitt (1998), American Economic Review, structural model of welfare and labor supply"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Extensive-margin responses of single mothers are among the largest in the labor-supply literature. Quasi-experimental EITC and welfare-reform studies and structural models typically imply participation elasticities around 0.4 to 1.0, with some higher estimates. I center the median near 0.6 with wide uncertainty reflecting heterogeneity across identification strategies, time periods, and the distinction between participation and hours responses."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Medium-run elasticity of employment/labor-force participation with respect to the net-of-tax wage for single mothers in the United States.",
  "point_estimate": 0.5,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.1,
    "p25": 0.3,
    "p50": 0.5,
    "p75": 0.8,
    "p95": 1.2
  },
  "citations": ["Eissa and Liebman (1996), Labor Supply Response to the Earned Income Tax Credit, QJE", "Meyer and Rosenbaum (2001), Welfare, the Earned Income Tax Credit, and the Labor Supply of Single Mothers, QJE", "Keane and Moffitt (1998), A Structural Model of Multiple Welfare Program Participation and Labor Supply, IER"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Single mothers exhibit among the largest extensive-margin labor supply responses in the literature. EITC quasi-experimental evidence implies participation elasticities with respect to after-tax wages roughly in the 0.5-1.0 range, with some decompositions of the 1990s employment surge at or above 1; structural welfare-labor supply models tend to be lower, around 0.2-0.5. I center the medium-run elasticity at about 0.5 with wide uncertainty reflecting variation across policy eras, estimation approaches, and whether the net-of-tax wage captures benefit phase-outs and welfare program interactions."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Medium-run elasticity of employment (participation/extensive margin) of U.S. single mothers with respect to a 1 percent change in the net-of-tax wage.",
  "point_estimate": 0.7,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.2,
    "p25": 0.45,
    "p50": 0.7,
    "p75": 1.0,
    "p95": 1.4
  },
  "citations": ["Eissa and Liebman (1996), QJE, on EITC and single mothers' labor force participation", "Meyer and Rosenbaum (2001), QJE, on welfare reform, EITC, and single mothers' employment", "Keane and Moffitt (1998), Econometrica, structural model of single mothers' labor supply and welfare participation"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Single mothers are among the most responsive groups at the extensive margin in the U.S. literature. Reduced-form work exploiting EITC expansions and 1990s welfare reform (Eissa-Liebman, Meyer-Rosenbaum) and structural models (Keane-Moffitt) imply participation elasticities with respect to net wages roughly in the 0.4-1.2 range, with central tendency near 0.7. Uncertainty is substantial because estimates vary with the identifying variation (EITC vs. welfare reform vs. wage variation), the horizon, and whether the medium run allows for adjustment beyond short-run responses; hence a wide but right-skewed interval."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Annual subjective discount factor beta used when calibrating a representative-household block (one-year utility discounting).",
  "point_estimate": 0.96,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.93,
    "p25": 0.95,
    "p50": 0.96,
    "p75": 0.975,
    "p95": 0.99
  },
  "citations": ["Cooley & Prescott (1995), Economic Growth and Business Cycles — annual beta ≈ 0.96", "Kydland & Prescott (1982) RBC calibration tradition", "Smets & Wouters (2007) — estimated annual discount factor closer to ~0.99"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Standard annual calibrations set beta ≈ 0.96 to imply a ~4% steady-state real interest rate (1/1.04). Estimated DSGE models often recover higher values (~0.97–0.995), while some heterogeneous-agent or behavioral calibrations go lower (~0.93–0.95), so uncertainty is concentrated around 0.95–0.98 with mass extending to 0.93 and 0.99."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Primary-earner substitution-response elasticity for earnings decile 2 in a U.S. microsimulation model",
  "point_estimate": 0.15,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.0,
    "p25": 0.05,
    "p50": 0.15,
    "p75": 0.25,
    "p95": 0.4
  },
  "citations": ["McClelland & Mok (2012), CBO Working Paper, 'A Review of Recent Research on Labor Supply Elasticities'", "Chetty (2012), 'Bounds on Elasticities with Optimization Frictions'", "CBO microsimulation practice of assigning substitution elasticities by earnings decile for primary earners"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Primary earners generally have low intensive-margin substitution elasticities; estimates for men/primary earners cluster near 0.1-0.3, and at low earnings (decile 2) optimization frictions and fixed work costs tend to push the effective value toward the lower end, so I center near 0.15 with a lower tail reaching zero and an upper tail allowing for moderate responsiveness where hours flexibility exists."
}

{
  "interpretation": "AR(1) persistence coefficient on log U.S. aggregate TFP measured at a quarterly frequency, as in standard log-linear RBC-style processes.",
  "point_estimate": 0.95,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.87,
    "p25": 0.92,
    "p50": 0.95,
    "p75": 0.97,
    "p95": 0.99
  },
  "citations": ["Prescott (1986), Theory Ahead of Business Cycle Measurement", "King & Rebelo (1999), Resuscitating Real Business Cycles", "Cooley & Prescott (1995), Economic Growth and Business Cycles"],
  "reasoning_summary": "Quarterly Solow-residual-based TFP series are highly autocorrelated, and standard RBC calibrations center the AR(1) coefficient near 0.95-0.97. Uncertainty spans lower values (~0.87-0.90) for utilization-adjusted or detrended measures and values near unity (~0.99) reflecting possible near-unit-root behavior in raw TFP."
}
